Hurricanes in the Caribbean:

A Data Analysis Project by Jex Pearce

Introduction:

While sailing in Grenada this past summer, I found myself constantly on edge due to the looming threat of hurricanes. The Caribbean hurricane season, which spans from July to late October, certainly kept me on high alert. Inspired by this experience, I thought of a compelling idea to chart the trajectories of recent hurricanes and to analyze the data to potentially unearth insights on climate change.

Regrettably, my search for a dataset featuring recent hurricanes yielded no results. However, I did find a dataset encompassing hurricane records from 1900 up to 2015. This dataset also happens to provide helpful snapshots of hurricane activities at six-hour intervals. To illustrate, take the example of 'Hurricane Emily,' which is documented across 22 rows of data, spanning a total duration of 132 hours (as 22 x 6 = 132).

The data is also a little inconsistent. While some unnamed typhoons are provided, the majority of the storms on this list are only added once the tropical storm turns into a Hurricane which is consequentially given a name to go by. *A hurricane is officially 'named' when the tropical storm typically exceeds a wind speed of 120 km/hr (75 mph).

You can also view the Python code I've written in Jupyter Notebook by clicking on the 'Show Code Cell' button.

As shown above, this dataset includes many features. The columns I will be analyzing the most include Latitude, Longitude, Date, Name, and Maximum Wind.

Note that it is messy. The 'Date' column is in a convoluted format, Latitude and Longitude have non-numerical values next to them, and the archaic hurricanes from the 1900s have inaccurate data. Data manipulation and cleaning is most certainly necessary.

Data Manipulation and Cleaning:

The first task is to convert the date to a format that is easier to read: 

data['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['Date'], format='%Y%m%d')
mask = (data['Date'] >= '1900-01-01')
filtereddata = data[mask]
data = filtereddata

The next step is to strip the 'Latitude' and 'Longitude' columns of non-numerical values and convert it to float form. (A float is a decimal). 

data['Longitude'] = data['Longitude'].map(lambda x: x.rstrip('W'))
data['Latitude'] = data['Latitude'].map(lambda x: x.rstrip('N'))
data['Latitude'] = data['Latitude'].map(lambda x: x.rstrip('S'))
data['Longitude'] = data['Longitude'].map(lambda x: x.rstrip('E'))
#converting to floats
data['Latitude'] = data['Latitude'].astype(float)
data['Longitude'] = data['Longitude'].astype(float)

Take note of the changes to the Date, Latitude, and Longitude columns. If we only want hurricanes in the Caribbean, we must make bounds for the Latitude and Longitude. 

latitude_lower_bound = 9
latitude_upper_bound = 26

latitude_filtered_data = data[
    (data['Latitude'].astype(float) >= latitude_lower_bound) &
    (data['Latitude'].astype(float) <= latitude_upper_bound)]

longitude_lower_bound = -86
longitude_upper_bound = -56

latitude_filtered_data['Longitude'] = -1 * latitude_filtered_data['Longitude']

lat_long_filtered_data = latitude_filtered_data[
    (latitude_filtered_data['Longitude'] >= longitude_lower_bound) &
    (latitude_filtered_data['Longitude'] <= longitude_upper_bound)]

In summary, this code takes the data and filters it based on latitude and longitude values. It first filters rows based on latitude, then converts the longitude values to negative, and filters rows based on longitude within the specified bounds. The shape of the resulting filtered dataset is printed at each step. 

#changing all data to strings for future 
all_columns = list(lat_long_filtered_data)  
lat_long_filtered_data.loc[:, all_columns] = lat_long_filtered_data[all_columns].astype(str)

# Replace all inaccuracies like -999 with NaN which python then removes automatically :)
lat_long_filtered_data = lat_long_filtered_data.replace('-999', np.nan)

# Remove -99 in the windspeed section
lat_long_filtered_data = lat_long_filtered_data.replace('-99', np.nan)

lat_long_filtered_data['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(lat_long_filtered_data['Date'])
#Creating a new column, this time called 'Year' which only has the Year from the date column in that associated row
lat_long_filtered_data['Year'] = lat_long_filtered_data['Date'].dt.year

As you can see, the line of best fit is upward, indicating a slight increase in the average number of hurricanes each year. (Possibly due to climate change!!) Although the outcome is obvious, I will do some Machine Learning with Linear Regression to show that this increasing trend stays true for future years.

Predicting the Line of Best Fit for Future Years with Linear Regression: 

x_fit = hurricanesinayear['Year'].values
y_fit = hurricanesinayear['Count'].values

#linear regression for existing years
existingmodel = LinearRegression()
existingmodel.fit(x_fit.reshape(-1, 1), y_fit.reshape(-1, 1))

#Predicting on the present data
predictedcounts = existingmodel.predict(x_fit.reshape(-1, 1))

# Create a DataFrame for the predicted values for existing years
predicteddataexisting = pd.DataFrame({'Year': x_fit, 'PredictedCount': predictedcounts.flatten()})

#Linear regression on existing data
model_all = LinearRegression()
model_all.fit(x_fit.reshape(-1, 1), y_fit.reshape(-1, 1))

#predicting # of hurricanes
futureyears = np.arange(hurricanesinayear['Year'].max() + 1, hurricanesinayear['Year'].max() + 41).reshape(-1, 1)
predictedcountsfuture = model_all.predict(futureyears)

#future data for predicted years
predicteddatafuture = pd.DataFrame({'Year': future_years.flatten(), 'PredictedCount': predictedcountsfuture.flatten()})

#plotting the line of best fit for the predicted and current
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.lineplot(x='Year', y='Count', data=hurricanesinayear, marker='o', color='blue', label='Number of Hurricanes')
sns.lineplot(x='Year', y='PredictedCount', data=predicteddataexisting, marker='o', color='red', label='Line of Best Fit (Existing Years)')
sns.lineplot(x='Year', y='PredictedCount', data=predicteddatafuture, marker='o', color='darkred', label='Predicted Count (Future Years)')

plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Number of Hurricanes')
plt.title('Number of Hurricanes by Year with Predictions')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()

plt.show()

As expected, the line of best fit continues its upward growth indicating an increase in hurricanes for future years.

Average Maximum Wind Speeds of Hurricanes by Year: 

#From now on I will just call lat_long_filtered_data "data" for simplicity.
data = lat_long_filtered_data
data['Year'] = data['Year'].astype(str)

# here I am replacing bad values with NaN and then dropping them using the "dropna" command
data['Maximum Wind'] = pd.to_numeric(data['Maximum Wind'], errors='coerce')
data = data.dropna(subset=['Maximum Wind'])

# finding the maximum wind speed for each hurricane in each year
maxwind = data.groupby(['Year', 'Name'])['Maximum Wind'].max().reset_index()

#calculating the average of the maximum wind speeds for each year
avgmaxwind = maxwind.groupby('Year')['Maximum Wind'].mean().reset_index()


plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.set_style("whitegrid")
sns.barplot(x='Year', y='Maximum Wind', data=avgmaxwind, ci=None)
plt.title('Average of Maximum Wind Speeds of Hurricanes by Year')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Average of Maximum Wind Speeds')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
#not sure why an error comes up. The graph still works but if someone could DM and tell me why! :)


Note that 1950 could be considered a fluke, as the weather measuring tools were still quite flimsy and experimental.

Predicting the Line of Best Fit for Average Maximum Wind Speeds using Linear Regression: 

# Perform linear regression to get the line of best fit
x = np.arange(len(avgmaxwind))
y = avgmaxwind['Maximum Wind']
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = linregress(x, y)
linebestfit = slope * x + intercept

#increasing the x axis for another 30 years in the future
futureyears = np.arange(
    int(avgmaxwind['Year'].max()) + 1,  # Start from the next year 
    int(avgmaxwind['Year'].max()) + 31  # predict for the next 30 yrs!
)
futureX = np.arange(len(avgmaxwind), len(avgmaxwind) + 30)

#predict for the next 30 simple formula 
futureY = slope * futureX + intercept

#plot for line of best fit
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(x, linebestfit, color='red', label=f'Line of Best Fit')
plt.plot(futureX, futureY, linestyle='--', color='blue', label='Predicted Years')

#this is just because i couldn't get it to automatically add the predicted years on the x-axis so i am doing it manually.
x_ticks = np.arange(0, len(avgmaxwind) + 30, 10)
x_tick_labels = list(map(str, avgmaxwind['Year'][::10])) + list(map(str, futureyears[::10]))
plt.xticks(x_ticks, x_tick_labels, rotation=45)


plt.title('Line of Best Fit for Average Maximum Wind Speeds by Year')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('The Average Maximum Wind Speed')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()

Slope of the line of best fit for the number of storms per year: 0.0278 Slope of the line of best fit for the average maximum wind per year: 0.0205

We can observe that the annual count of storms is rising at a somewhat faster pace compared to the yearly maximum wind speed averages. Nevertheless, it's crucial to note that both of these slope values are positive and are on the upward trend. Consequently, we can anticipate a future with an increase in both the frequency and strength of hurricanes. While these findings may appear self-evident, the gratification of substantiating climate change with concrete data is quite satisfying!

Hurricane Path Plots for 2010-2015: 

data = lat_long_filtered_data
data['Year'] = data['Date'].dt.year

yearrange = data[
    (data['Year'] >= 2010) &
    (data['Year'] <= 2015)
]

# Get unique hurricane names
hurricanenames = yearrange['Name'].unique()

# Create a custom color palette with a broad range of distinct colors
customcolors = px.colors.qualitative.Dark24  # You can choose a different palette if needed
customcolormapping = {name: customcolors[i % len(customcolors)] for i, name in enumerate(hurricanenames)}

yearrange = yearrange.copy()

# Add a new 'Color' column based on the 'StormName' column
yearrange['Color'] = yearrange['Name'].map(customcolormapping)

fig = go.Figure(data=go.Scattergeo(
    lat=yearrange['Latitude'],
    lon=yearrange['Longitude'],
    text=yearrange['Name'],  # Display the hurricane names on hover
    mode='markers',
    marker=dict(
        size=5,
        opacity=0.7,
        color=yearrange['Color']  # Use the assigned color
    )
))

fig.update_geos(
    center=dict(lon=-71, lat=17),
    lataxis_range=[7, 29],
    lonaxis_range=[-88, -55]
)

fig.update_layout(
    title='Hurricane Tracks (2010-2015)',
    geo=dict(
        showcoastlines=True,
        coastlinecolor="Black",
        showland=True,
        landcolor="lightgray",
    )
)

# Show the plot
fig.show()

The map would look rightfully cramped if I included all the years, so I decided to do 5 year intervals.

Hurricane Tracks in 2010-2015: 

fig = go.Figure()

for hurricanenames, group in yearrange.groupby('Name'):
    fig.add_trace(go.Scattergeo(
        lat=group['Latitude'],
        lon=group['Longitude'],
        text=group['Name'],  # Display the hurricane names on hover
        mode='lines',  # Display only lines (no markers)
        line=dict(color=group['Color'].iloc[0]),  # Use the assigned color for the entire hurricane path
        name=hurricanenames  # Label each hurricane path
    ))

fig.update_geos(
    center=dict(lon=-71, lat=17),
    lataxis_range=[7, 29],
    lonaxis_range=[-88, -55]
)

fig.update_layout(
    title='Hurricane Tracks (2010-2015) with Paths (No Dots)',
    geo=dict(
        showcoastlines=True,
        coastlinecolor="Black",

    )
)

The Top 10 Strongest Hurricanes:

Let's find out which hurricanes had the highest maximum wind! 

# Sort the data by maximum wind speed in descending order
maxwinddata = data.sort_values(by='Maximum Wind', ascending=False)
top10hurricanes = maxwinddata.groupby('Name').head(1).head(10)
top10hurricanenames = top10hurricanes['Name']
print(top10hurricanenames)
3277 GILBERT 4932 WILMA 2672 ALLEN 4160 MITCH 5110 FELIX 3599 ANDREW 2558 DAVID 5086 DEAN 4751 IVAN 4606 ISABEL Name: Name, dtype: object

Hurricane GILBERT of 1988 is officially the strongest hurricane ever recorded, with a top speed of 298 km/hr (185 mph)! However, most sources will say that WILMA was actually the strongest, as her maximum wind of 295 km/hr (183 mph), while slightly less than GILBERT, kept up her incredible speed for a longer amount of time.

Some other famous hurricanes to hit the Caribbean in this list include Hurricane IVAN, whose maximum speed was 270 km/hr (168 mph), and Hurricane MITCH of 1998 with a maximum speed of 285 hm/hr (177 mph) which suffered 22,000 casualties with the majority being in Honduras. Hurricane MITCH is actually the second deadliest hurricane to ever hit the Caribbean, with the Great Hurricane of 1780 topping it with 25,000 casualties.

The Top 10 Strongest Hurricanes and Their Paths: 

hurricanepaths = []
# do a for loop for the 10 hurricanes and retrieve their paths.
for top10hurricanenames in top10hurricanes['Name']:
    # filtering for current hurricane
    hurricanedata = maxwinddata[maxwinddata['Name'] == top10hurricanenames]
    # sorting and removing duplicates
    hurricanedata = hurricanedata.sort_values(by='Date')
    hurricanedata = hurricanedata.drop_duplicates(subset=['Latitude', 'Longitude'])
    
    trace = go.Scattergeo(
        lat=hurricanedata['Latitude'],
        lon=hurricanedata['Longitude'],
        text=hurricanedata['Name'],  #for hovering
        mode='markers',
        name=top10hurricanenames)  #this is for the label box, to label each name and colour code it
    
    
    #add trace to list of paths
    hurricanepaths.append(trace)

# graph hurricane paths in geograph
fig = go.Figure(hurricanepaths)

fig.update_geos(
    center=dict(lon=-71, lat=17),
    lataxis_range=[7, 29],
    lonaxis_range=[-88, -55])
fig.update_layout(
    title='Top 10 Hurricanes with the Highest Maximum Wind Speeds',
    geo=dict(
        showcoastlines=True,
        coastlinecolor="Black",
        showland=True,
        landcolor="lightgray",))
